SIMPLE: frush
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Frush
<hw>Frush</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>froisser</ets> to bruise. Cf. <er>Froise</er>.]</ety> <def>To
batter; to break in pieces.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I like thine armor well;⟦br⟧
I'll <qex>frush</qex> it and unlock the rivets all.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frush</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Frush
<hw>Frush</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Easily broken; brittle;
crisp.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frush</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Frush
<hw>Frush</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Noise; clatter; crash.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Southey.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frush</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Frush
<hw>Frush</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OE. <ets>frosch</ets>,
<ets>frosk</ets>, a frog (the animal), G. <ets>frosch</ets> frog (the
animal), also carney or lampass of horses. See <er>Frog</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>, 2.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Far.)</fld> <def>The frog of
a horse's foot.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A discharge of a fetid or ichorous matter from the
frog of a horse's foot; -- also called
<altname>thrush.</altname></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frustrable</ent>⟦br⟧
